"Restrictive Cardiomyopathy"
]
},
"children":[
{
"type":"section",
"id":"mk19_bb_cv_s8_1",
"title":{
"__html":"Diagnosis"
},
"titleNode":{
"type":"section-title",
"hlId":"523223",
"children":[
"Diagnosis"
]
},
"children":[
{
"type":"p",
"hlId":"663c92",
"children":[
"Presenting symptoms include dyspnea, peripheral edema, and exercise intolerance. Hepatomegaly and ascites may be late findings. Jugular veins may engorge with inspiration (Kussmaul sign)."
]
},
{
"type":"p",
"hlId":"ce8b15",
"children":[
"Primary restrictive cardiomyopathy must be differentiated from other conditions with restrictive physiology."
]
},
{
"type":"p",
"hlId":"0eaa51",
"children":[
"Restriction and normal wall size:"
]
},
{
"type":"list",
"children":[
" ",
{
"type":"list-item",
"hlId":"324178",
"children":[
"radiation-induced fibrosis"
]
},
" ",
{
"type":"list-item",
"hlId":"f8431d",
"children":[
"eosinophilic diseases"
]
},
" ",
{
"type":"list-item",
"hlId":"a29bb3",
"children":[
"hemochromatosis"
]
},
" "
]
},
{
"type":"p",
"hlId":"774040",
"children":[
"Restriction and increased wall thickness:"
]
},
{
"type":"list",
"children":[
" ",
{
"type":"list-item",
"hlId":"78b140",
"children":[
"amyloidosis"
]
},
" "
]
}
]
},
{
"type":"section",
"id":"mk19_bb_cv_s8_2",
"title":{
"__html":"Testing"
},
"titleNode":{
"type":"section-title",
"hlId":"fa6a5a",
"children":[
"Testing"
]
},
"children":[
{
"type":"p",
"hlId":"d8bdd9",
"children":[
"Echocardiogram shows biatrial enlargement and severe diastolic dysfunction in the setting of normal ventricular size, wall thickness, and systolic function. ",
{
"type":"abbreviation",
"title":"pulmonary hypertension",
"children":[
"PH"
]
},
" is commonly present, as are tricuspid and mitral valve regurgitation."
]
},
{
"type":"inline-wrap",
"wrapId":"1",
"contentIds":[
"mk19_bb_cv_s8_inline_t1"
],
"forceOpen":true
},
{
"type":"p",
"hlId":"540b3b",
"children":[
"Restrictive cardiomyopathy must be differentiated from constrictive pericarditis (see Cardiac Effusion and Tamponade and Constrictive Pericarditis sections)."
]
}
]
},
{
"type":"section",
"id":"mk19_bb_cv_s8_3",
"title":{
"__html":"Treatment"
},
"titleNode":{
"type":"section-title",
"hlId":"4c4ac0",
"children":[
"Treatment"
]
},
"children":[
{
"type":"p",
"hlId":"103e2a",
"children":[
"Treat the underlying disorder when present and any underlying disease or condition that affects diastolic function (",
{
"type":"no-wrap",
"children":[
{
"type":"abbreviation",
"title":"atrial fibrillation",
"children":[
"AF"
]
},
","
]
},
" hypertension, diabetes, ischemic heart disease). Loop diuretics are used to treat dyspnea and peripheral edema. Î²-Blockers or nondihydropyridine calcium channel antagonists may enhance diastolic function."
]
}
]
},
{
"type":"section",
"id":"mk19_bb_cv_s8_4",
"title":{
"__html":"Test Yourself"
},
"titleNode":{
"type":"section-title",
"hlId":"7866cc",
"children":[
"Test Yourself"
]
},
"children":[
{
"type":"p",
"hlId":"76331c",
"class":"test",
"children":[
"A 63-year-old man develops dyspnea and fatigue. Physical examination shows ",
{
"type":"no-wrap",
"children":[
{
"type":"abbreviation",
"title":"jugular venous distention",
"children":[
"JVD"
]
},
","
]
},
" a prominent jugular ",
{
"type":"tag",
"tagName":"i",
"attrs":{
},
"children":[
"a"
]
},
" wave, a prominent S",
{
"type":"tag",
"tagName":"sub",
"attrs":{
},
"children":[
"4"
]
},
", and a grade 2/6 holosystolic murmur at the left sternal border. The lungs are clear. Other findings include an enlarged, tender liver; petechiae over the feet; and periorbital ecchymoses."
]
},
{
"type":"p",
"hlId":"5f3f6c",
"class":"test_answer",
"children":[
{
"type":"tag",
"tagName":"b",
"attrs":{
},
"children":[
"Answer:"
]
},
" ",
"The diagnosis is ",
{
"type":"abbreviation",
"title":"amyloidosis immunoglobulin light-chain amyloidosis",
"children":[
"AL"
]
},
" amyloid cardiomyopathy, indicated by the noncardiac symptoms and signs."
]
},
{
"type":"inline-wrap",
"wrapId":"2",
"contentIds":[
"mk19_bb_cv_f05"
],
"forceOpen":true
}
]
}
]
